<br>
Maybe not red.. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   But the more I look at the van the more it needs some kind of a paintscheme. Perhaps the logo of whomever's base this is.<br>
<br>
EtherealE,<br>
<br>
Flying characters / objects are alright as long as they can fit into the picture. Their size in the picture should be measured the same way as for those who are on the ground - pick a spot in the air, then create the 2 meter guide along the ground beneath the character and resize them to the proper scale with it. Technically the higher the character would be the smaller they were, but there's so little elevation difference in this picture between the camera level and the highest point that I think we can ignore it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Durakken,<br>
<br>
True enough, the background could have featured something else than a machine bay, but I'm not sure what kind of a background could have been suitable for both futuristic and medieval characters, if that's what you meant? Besides, right now we're working with my limited background artist's skills - next time, should it come, we can hopefully rely on someone who has more experience in creating good backgrounds <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
MontrealBMXER,<br>
<br>
I took the liberty to match your sketch into the background accordingly to my guidelines, and assuming your character is a little bit shorter than 2 meters (somewhere between 190 and 200cm), <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.puonti.net/mbmx.jpg">this</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is how he'd look.<br>
<br>
It's not easy to figure out how tall a crouching character would be, so this is just an estimate (for three different spots on top of the van).<br>
<br>
When you finalize the character, remember that his &quot;rear&quot; foot should be lower than his &quot;front&quot; foot, because the van's roof is slanted in this perspective. <p><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Want to color my lineart?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Otherwise alter something I've created? Please read my <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>profile</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> for further information before proceeding!</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jspuonti>JSPuonti</A> at: 2/22/03 11:23:53 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eolatria>Eolatria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/23/03 4:23:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm23.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8338.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Community project thingamajig (plenty of room left :)</span><hr size=1> Great, I´ll join!<br>
